LXXIII. The most esteemed variety is the Cretan3 next comes the Egyptian. This in season— ing takes the place of lovage. To burn it and inhale 1116 fumes through the nostrils relieves headache. Evenor recommends its pounded root to be applied to fluxes of the eyes3 Iollas recommends a similar application of the plant itself with saffron and wine3 by itself, with only pearl barley added, he prescribes it for violent fluxes and for extraction of anything which has got into the eyes. Applied in water it also removes a cancerous growth in the nostril. Used as a gargle with hyssop and honey in vinegar it relieves quinsies3 it is poured with rose oil into the ears; phlegm in the chest is cleared away by parched anise taken with honey. For a cough it is better 10 pound up in honey fifty bitter almonds, peeled, with an acetabulum of anise.
